        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Content decay</strong> is the gradual decline in organic search performance of pages that once ranked well. Rankings drop, clicks fall, conversions taper — often within 6-12 months of a page's peak. Causes: outdated information, fresher competitor content, shifting search intent, or algorithm updates that change what wins.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Traffic loss (pos 3→8)</div>
            <div class="tms-value">~70% CTR drop</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Content</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Republish lift</div>
            <div class="tms-value">+106% (HubSpot)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Every page that ranks eventually stops ranking — unless a human intervenes. The teams that win at organic search are not the ones publishing the most; they are the ones who catch decay before it becomes invisibility.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is content decay?</h2>
        <p>Content decay is the process by which web pages that once drove consistent organic traffic gradually lose their search performance. Rankings drop, click-through rates fall, and conversions dry up — often over weeks or months, until the page effectively disappears from search results.</p>
        <p>Decay is not a penalty. Google is not punishing the page. The page is simply losing a competition it used to win because the field has changed underneath it.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>New competitors</strong> publish more thorough versions.</li>
          <li><strong>Facts inside the page</strong> — statistics, prices, screenshots, year references — go stale.</li>
          <li><strong>User intent</strong> for the query shifts subtly.</li>
          <li><strong>Backlinks disappear</strong> as sites re-organise or die.</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Scale of the problem</div>
          <p>Ahrefs analysis shows <strong>66.5% of pages receive zero Google traffic</strong>. A large portion of that is not new content that never ranked — it is old content that used to rank and then decayed there.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why content decay matters</h2>
        <p>Decay is expensive precisely because it happens quietly. Five reasons every content team monitors it:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Compounded traffic loss.</strong> A page falling from position 3 to position 8 loses roughly 70% of its clicks — even though it is still on page one.</li>
          <li><strong>Revenue impact.</strong> High-performing lead-generating content stops converting the moment it stops ranking.</li>
          <li><strong>Competitive displacement.</strong> The ranking slot does not stay empty — a competitor's fresher page takes it.</li>
          <li><strong>Wasted authority.</strong> A page with 30 backlinks earning nothing is authority sitting on the shelf.</li>
          <li><strong>Fix cost is 10x lower than build cost.</strong> Refreshing a decayed page is cheaper than researching, writing, and ranking a new one.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How content decay actually happens</h2>
        <p>Decay is triggered by one or more of five mechanisms — often stacking.</p>
        <h3>1. Outdated information</h3>
        <p>Statistics, product prices, feature lists, year references (any page with "2024" in the title). Google reads these as staleness signals; readers bounce faster; both feed back into lower rankings.</p>
        <h3>2. Competitor freshness</h3>
        <p>A rival publishes a longer, more current, better-structured article on the same query. Even if your page is technically stronger, "recently updated" plus reasonable depth often wins.</p>
        <h3>3. Search intent shift</h3>
        <p>Google's SERPs for a query evolve. A term that once returned blog posts now returns tools; a term that returned lists now returns videos. Your page no longer matches what searchers want.</p>
        <h3>4. Algorithm updates</h3>
        <p>Core updates re-weight quality signals. Pages that were "good enough" before become insufficient after. <a href="/glossary/helpful-content-system/">Helpful content</a> and <a href="/glossary/e-e-a-t/">E-E-A-T</a> updates have both caused mass cliff-drops.</p>
        <h3>5. Link profile weakness</h3>
        <p>External sites reorganize; backlinks 404 or move; internal links get orphaned during redesigns; competitor pages accumulate authority faster. The result: your authority relative to the page you're competing with shrinks.</p>

        <h2 id="types">Types of content decay patterns</h2>
        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Pattern</th><th>Signature</th><th>Common cause</th><th>Fix priority</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="row-highlight"><td><strong>Slow bleed</strong></td><td>1-2 position drops per quarter over 6-18 months</td><td>Staleness + competitor pressure</td><td>Refresh</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Cliff drop</strong></td><td>Sudden 5-20 position loss in one week</td><td>Algorithm update</td><td>Diagnose update criteria first</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Seasonal reset</strong></td><td>Spikes and drops on calendar cycle</td><td>Seasonal intent</td><td>Update pre-season</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Statistical obsolescence</strong></td><td>Bounce rate spike, dwell time drop</td><td>Data references outdated</td><td>Refresh numbers</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Format decay</strong></td><td>Impressions steady, CTR falling</td><td>SERPs added video/tools</td><td>Add multimedia + schema</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Cannibalisation drop</strong></td><td>New page competing on same query</td><td>Internal duplicate content</td><td>Merge or noindex duplicates</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real content decay examples</h2>
        <h3>1. Accounting firm's tax-deduction guide</h3>
        <p>Ranked #3 for "small business tax deductions" for two years. In year three, three competitors published 2026-updated versions. Position fell to #11 in a single quarter — organic traffic dropped 68%.</p>
        <h3>2. SaaS pricing comparison page</h3>
        <p>Ranked #5 for a competitor comparison query. The competitor restructured their pricing, making the page's numbers wrong. Bounce rate spiked, position fell to page 2 within 5 months. A single refresh of the pricing table restored the #5 rank.</p>
        <h3>3. Realtor's neighborhood guide</h3>
        <p>Ranked in the local pack for 18 months. Portals like Zillow and Realtor.com published longer interactive versions. The page slid from #6 to #14 over 4 months — reversed after adding market-stat tables, embedded maps, and structured data.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Content decay vs. content pruning — different jobs</h2>
        <p>Both address underperforming content. One is the problem, one is a solution.</p>
        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Content decay</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Passive problem — happens on its own</li>
              <li>Symptom: traffic decline on old top-performers</li>
              <li>Response: refresh and republish</li>
              <li>Goal: restore lost rankings</li>
              <li>Applied to: pages worth saving</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4><a href="/glossary/content-pruning/">Content pruning</a></h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Active solution — deliberate action</li>
              <li>Signal: no traffic, no links, no purpose</li>
              <li>Response: remove, merge, or noindex</li>
              <li>Goal: strengthen overall site quality</li>
              <li>Applied to: pages beyond saving</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 best practices to combat content decay</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Set up quarterly decay audits.</strong> Filter Search Console for pages losing 20%+ clicks year-over-year. Investigate the top 20.</li>
          <li><strong>Prioritise the highest-traffic decayers first.</strong> Fixing a page that lost 500 monthly clicks is worth more than fixing five that lost 50 each.</li>
          <li><strong>Refresh the parts that decayed, not the whole page.</strong> Update stats, screenshots, dates, examples, prices. Keep the URL, meta, and any high-performing sections intact.</li>
          <li><strong>Add what competitors now include.</strong> Comparison table, FAQ block, embedded video, schema markup. Match the SERP's current expectations.</li>
          <li><strong>Republish with a new "last updated" date.</strong> Show <code>dateModified</code> in JSON-LD schema and on-page — Google reads both.</li>
          <li><strong>Publish consistently in the same topic cluster.</strong> New content strengthens internal linking and topical authority, which slows decay across the whole cluster.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common trap — updating the date without updating the content</div>
          <p>Changing the year in the title and the <code>dateModified</code> field without substantially refreshing the content is one of the tactics Google explicitly calls out as manipulation. Detected consistently, it can cause rankings to drop further rather than recover.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common content decay mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Ignoring decay until it becomes zero traffic.</strong> Catching a 20% drop is 5x cheaper than catching an 80% drop.</li>
          <li><strong>Rewriting instead of refreshing.</strong> Full rewrites reset the URL's history if you change slugs. Refresh in place.</li>
          <li><strong>Only monitoring position, not clicks.</strong> A page can hold position and still lose 30% of clicks if the SERP added AI Overviews.</li>
          <li><strong>Treating every declining page as decay.</strong> Some pages decline because query volume itself dropped — check impressions before assuming decay.</li>
          <li><strong>Publishing new content while ignoring old decayers.</strong> The math almost always favours refreshing over rebuilding.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)"><span class="faq-q-text">How quickly does content decay?</span><span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Most news, statistical, and time-sensitive content loses 30-50% of its traffic within 6-12 months. Evergreen how-to content can hold rankings for 2-3 years before requiring an update.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)"><span class="faq-q-text">Can content decay be reversed?</span><span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Yes. HubSpot's historical optimization program increased organic traffic by 106% on average by republishing updated posts. Refreshing stats, screenshots, and dates typically restores 60-80% of lost rankings.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)"><span class="faq-q-text">How do I detect content decay early?</span><span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Open Google Search Console's Performance report, filter the last 6 months, sort by clicks difference year-over-year. Pages showing 20%+ declines with stable impressions are primary decay candidates.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)"><span class="faq-q-text">What is the difference between content decay and content pruning?</span><span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Content decay is the passive traffic decline. Content pruning is the deliberate act of removing, merging, or noindexing underperforming content to strengthen the site's overall quality.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)"><span class="faq-q-text">Does publishing more content prevent decay?</span><span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Volume alone does not prevent decay. Consistent publishing builds topical authority and stronger internal linking, which slows decay across the cluster. Combine new publishing with quarterly refreshes.</p></div></div>
          </div>
        </div>

